{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FMNTC4xnMhRav7qQEL3pXc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The pod's spec image is `rabbitmq:3.12-management` but the StatefulSet template says `rabbitmq:3.9-management`. This means the rollback happened in the StatefulSet template, but the actual pod (which was updated during the first rollout) still has the 3.12 image.\n\nThe situation is: With `maxUnavailable: 3`, the StatefulSet controller terminated rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 (they're gone), but rabbitmq-0 is still in CrashLoopBackOff with the 3.12 image. \n\nThe rollback changed the template to 3.9, but the rollout is still in progress—it deleted all three pods starting with the highest ordinal, created new ones with 3.12 which failed, and with `maxUnavailable: 3` it may have terminated them all simultaneously rather than sequentially.\n\nNow I see the current state: rabbitmq-0 is still running 3.12 from the forward rollout, while rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 were deleted. Since the StatefulSet template now specifies 3.9 after the rollback, the controller needs to continue by deleting rabbitmq-0 and recreating it with 3.9, then waiting for it to stabilize before recreating the remaining pods in order.\n\nBut there's a critical problem: the 3.12 image crashed during startup before it could fully initialize, so it may have written partial or corrupted feature flag state to the PVC that 3.9 won't be able to interpret. Looking at the error logs, the 3.12 image failed because the `classic_mirrored_queue_version` feature flag wasn't enabled before the upgrade attempt—this is exactly the kind of incompatibility that would prevent a downgrade.\n\nThe real issue is that the current pod is still running 3.12 even though the StatefulSet template was rolled back to 3.9, so the pod hasn't been restarted with the new image yet. I see the issue now—since rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 don't exist, the rolling update has to recreate them first with the new 3.9 spec before it can get to updating rabbitmq-0, which is why rabbitmq-0 is still stuck on 3.12 waiting for the earlier pods to come up. Wait, I need to reconsider what's actually running. The pod rabbitmq-0 is still on 3.12, not 3.9. Looking back at the logs from after the rollback, that warning message about the Erlang cookie is from 3.12, and it's showing the feature flags error—so the issue isn't that 3.9 is crashing, it's that 3.12 is still running and hitting this compatibility problem.\n\nNow I'm realizing the StatefulSet update process: since rabbitmq-1 and rabbitmq-2 don't exist yet, they'll be created with the 3.9 spec. But with RollingUpdate, the update happens in descending ordinal order, so it would try to update pod-2 first—except pod-2 doesn't exist. Let me think through what actually happens when pods are missing during a rolling update.\n\nThe key constraint is OrderedReady: each pod must be Running and Ready before moving to the next one. When the controller creates pod-2 with 3.9, it'll use the existing PVC (data-rabbitmq-2) which has the 3.9 data from before. That should work fine. But I'm wondering if the 3.12 pod-0 that's currently crashing is somehow blocking the creation of the missing pods or corrupting the shared state.\n\nActually, thinking through the forward rollout sequence with `maxUnavailable: 3` — all three pods could be updated simultaneously, meaning pod-2 and pod-1 get deleted and recreated with 3.12 at the same time as pod-0. If that's what happened, then the PVC data might have been left in an inconsistent state when 3.12 tried to initialize the cluster. But with maxUnavailable=3, all three pods should be able to fail simultaneously during the rollout. I'm realizing the OrderedReady policy might be constraining the creation order—the controller probably can't create pod-1 until pod-2 is ready, and can't create pod-0 until pod-1 is ready, which explains why only pod-0 exists in the CrashLoopBackOff state at the start of the rollback.\n\nNow I need to figure out what actually happened: pod-0 started with 3.12, crashed during feature flag registry initialization, and I'm not sure what state the PVCs are in. Since 3.12 crashed before fully booting, it might have partially written data that could corrupt the rollback to 3.9.\n\nThe real issue is that the rolling update back to 3.9 seems stuck—it's probably waiting for the higher-ordinal pods to be created first, but since pods 1 and 2 don't exist, the StatefulSet controller might be in a deadlock state.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":580,"cache_read_input_tokens":48045,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":580},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7477e209-d8ca-4ef9-8a94-60016f704d9e","uuid":"a18b799b-6b91-46ad-b84c-2366e17cd43c","request_id":"req_011CcPzHYic1TCaxcWhKFaNy"}
