{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Q84gBBdc3qcxXXQxQdbvwL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pod is running but not ready. The logs show:\n- It's waiting for Mnesia tables\n- There are errors about `rabbit_durable_queue` - it's waiting for all 3 nodes to come up\n\nThis is normal! The node is waiting for nodes 1 and 2 to join before Mnesia tables are ready. With OrderedReady policy, pod-1 won't start until pod-0 is ready. But pod-0 won't be ready until all nodes are available (Mnesia tables wait).\n\nThis is a classic bootstrap deadlock for a RabbitMQ cluster where it requires a quorum to start.\nSo the issue is clear: with OrderedReady, the pods start sequentially, but pod-0 can't become Ready until it has quorum from the other nodes. Pod-1 won't even start until pod-0 is Ready, creating a circular dependency. I could switch to Parallel policy to let all pods start simultaneously, but that requires deleting and recreating the StatefulSet since podManagementPolicy can't be changed in-place.\n\nBut wait—the original 3.9 deployment worked fine with OrderedReady, so there must be something different about how RabbitMQ 3.9 handles initial startup versus the newer version. Let me think about what happens when pod-0 starts for the first time.\n\nOn first startup with an empty PVC, pod-0 forms its own cluster and becomes ready. Then pod-1 joins and becomes ready, followed by pod-2. But now after the restart, pod-0's PVC still has the cluster membership data for nodes 1 and 2. When it restarts, it tries to sync Mnesia tables with those nodes, but they haven't started yet because of the OrderedReady policy. So it keeps retrying and timing out.\n\nThe standard RabbitMQ solution would be using Kubernetes peer discovery to handle this, but that doesn't fully solve the Mnesia sync issue. Let me check if the node is actually still running despite the timeout messages.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the core problem: the PVCs contain the original 3.9 cluster data with all three nodes in the metadata. When pod-0 restarts, it knows about nodes 1 and 2 and waits for them to rejoin. I could reset the Mnesia database on pod-0 to start fresh, but that would lose the queue data. I need to preserve what was working in the 3.9 state.\n\nThe original StatefulSet worked because pod-0 started on a clean PVC with no cluster memory, so it formed its own single-node cluster first. Then pods 1 and 2 discovered and joined it. But now pod-0 has cluster memory of all three nodes, so it's trying to rejoin an existing cluster rather than form a new one—which requires the other nodes to be running.\n\nI could wait for the Mnesia timeout to expire and hope pod-0 force-boots as the cluster leader, or I could try using `rabbitmqctl force_boot` to manually force it. The pod is actually running (just not passing readiness checks), so maybe I can exec into it and run the command directly. The issue is that `rabbit_table:wait` is blocking on Mnesia table copies becoming available, which won't happen until the other pods start—but they're stuck waiting for pod-0 to be Ready due to the OrderedReady policy. After 9 retries at 30 seconds each, pod-0 will fail if it doesn't become Ready. I need to break this deadlock, either by forcing pod-0 to boot independently, deleting its PVC to start fresh, or temporarily changing the pod management policy to allow parallel startup. I'm realizing the core issue: RabbitMQ 3.9 on pod-0 is stuck trying to sync with the other pods before it can become Ready, but those pods can't start due to the OrderedReady policy. The real solution is to use `force_boot` to manually bootstrap pod-0, which will break the deadlock and let the cluster recover. into it and check the actual state of the RabbitMQ process. The real issue is that pod-0 has the full cluster view in its Mnesia data from the original setup, so when it restarts after scaling, it's trying to sync with nodes 1 and 2 that aren't ready yet. Once the Mnesia timeout window expires after multiple retry cycles, pod-0 will either crash into CrashLoopBackOff or attempt a partial boot with just its local data—I should wait to see which happens.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1595,"cache_read_input_tokens":54793,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1595},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7477e209-d8ca-4ef9-8a94-60016f704d9e","uuid":"71783763-eb0c-4a3e-8404-7aa7eec1d58e","request_id":"req_011CcPzo82tMGuzpBi4tQu2L"}
